The resultant intensity is given by
\(\mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{R}}=\mathrm{I}_{1}+\mathrm{I}_{2}+2 \sqrt{I_{1} I_{2}} \mathrm{cos} \delta\)
\(\Rightarrow 7 \mathrm{I}=\mathrm{I}+9 \mathrm{I}+2 \times 3 \mathrm{I} \cos \delta\)
\(\cos \delta=-1 / 2\)
\(\delta=2 \pi / 3=120^{\circ}\)

Force exerted on a charged particle moving in a magnetic field

\(\overrightarrow{F} =q\left(\overrightarrow{v\, } \times \overrightarrow{B}\right) \)

Since the force is perpendicular to the direction of velocity of charged particle, the trajectory of particle is circle provided the direction of initial velocity of the particle is perpendicular to the magnetic field.

If the initial velocity of the particle had not been perpendicular to magnetic field, the trajectory would have been helical.

But, \(x = 0 \) doesn't satisfy original equation. So, no root.

quest_title: A hole of radius R/2 is cut from a thin circular plate of radius R. The mass of remaining plate is M. The moment of inertia of plate about axis through O and perpendicular to plate is
explanation_txt:
Let, \(\sigma\) be the mass per unit area.
Then
\(M=\pi R^{2} \sigma-\pi\left(\cfrac{R}{2}\right)^{2} \sigma\)

\(\qquad=\cfrac{3}{4} \pi \mathrm{R}^{2} \sigma\)

\(\therefore \pi \mathrm{R}^{2} \sigma=\cfrac{4 M}{3}\)

Moment of inertia due to whole plate

\(\begin{aligned}\left(\mathrm{I}_{1}\right) &=1 / 2 \pi \mathrm{R}^{2} \sigma \mathrm{R}^{2} \\ &=\cfrac{2}{3} M R^{2} \end{aligned}\)

Moment of inertia hole \(\left(\mathrm{I}_{2}\right)=\mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{cm}}+\mathrm{m}^{\prime}\left(\cfrac{R}{2}\right)^2\)

\(=1 / 2 \pi\left(\cfrac{R}{2}\right)^{2} \sigma \cfrac{R^{2}}{4}+\pi\left(\cfrac{R}{2}\right)^{2} \sigma \cfrac{R^{2}}{4}\)
\(=\cfrac{\pi \mathrm{R}^{2} \sigma \mathrm{R}^{2}+2 \pi \mathrm{R}^{2} \sigma \mathrm{R}^{2}}{32}\)
\(=\cfrac{3 \pi R^{2} \sigma R^{2}}{32}=\cfrac{4 M R^{2} \times 3}{3 \times 32}=\cfrac{M R^{2}}{8}\)

\(\therefore\) Moment of inertia \((\mathrm{I})=\mathrm{I}_{1}-\mathrm{I}_{2}\)
\(=\cfrac{2}{3} M R^{2}-\cfrac{M R^{2}}{8}\)

\(=\cfrac{16 \mathrm{MR}^{2}-3 \mathrm{MR}^{2}}{24}=\cfrac{13}{24} \mathrm{MR}^{2}\)
\(=\cfrac{13}{24} M R^{2}\)

quest_title: The equation of the parabola whose vertex is at (2, –1) and focus at (2, –3) is
explanation_txt:
The common co-ordinate of \( S(2,-3) \) and \( V(2,-1) \) is \( x= 2 \) which is axis. The parabola with \( x=h \) as axis is \( (x-h)^2=4a(y-k) \) where \(a\) is distance between focus and vertex, \( (h,k) \) is vertex. So, \( a =\pm \sqrt{(2-2)^2+(-3+1)^2} = 2\) Since focus is below vertex, negative sign is chosen. So, \(a=-2 \). And \( (h,k) = (2,-1) \).

So, equation is:

\( (x-2)^2 = -8(y+1) \\ \Rightarrow x^2 - 4x + 4 + 8y + 8 = 0 \\ \Rightarrow x^2 - 4x +8y +12=0\)
